ling account draws readers into the social, economic, religious, and political interactions that defined the European colonial experience in India and elsewhere. Her portrayal of imperial sovereignty in France's colonies as it played out in the life of one beleaguered family allows readers to witness interactions between colonial officials and locals. Students and scholars of the history of colonialism, religion, capitalism, and law will find Agmon's narrative of European imperialism of great interest.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFrenchzIndiazPuducherry (Union Territory)xHistoryy18th century. 4aEarly American & Colonial History. 4aHistory. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aPondicherry, colonialism, trade, missionaries, intermediaries, The Nayiniyappa Affair.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501713071zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de GruyterzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501713071zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501713071/original  a978-3-11-066587-1 Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA